# Code Quality Standards

## Strict Type Safety
- Never use `any`. Type every variable, parameter, and return value explicitly.
- Never use type casting (`as`). Use type guards, narrowing, or generics instead.
- Strict mode enabled; build errors fail the build.

## File & Function Size Limits
- **Functions**: max 500 lines. Break large functions into smaller, composable helpers.
- **Files**: max 2500 lines. Split into modules if approaching the limit.
- Prefer early returns to reduce nesting depth.

## Environment & Logging
- In library packages: avoid `process.env` and `console.*` in published code; use dependency injection or pass config. Tests and scripts may use them.
- When integrating with apps: use project env and logging utilities; see CONTRIBUTING for package layout.

## Comments & Naming
- Only meaningful comments: logical steps, non-obvious "why" reasoning. No trivial restatements. No emoji in code or comments.
- Private/protected: use TypeScript `private`/`protected`; do not prefix with underscores.
- Naming: PascalCase for classes; camelCase for functions/variables; SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants; dot-separated filenames (e.g. `env.utils.ts`).

## Package Conventions (see CONTRIBUTING.md)
- Layout: `src/{client,server,shared}/`, `__tests__/` mirroring src, Biome for lint/format, 80% coverage.
- Subpath exports: `@simpill/name.utils`, `@simpill/name.utils/client`, `/server`, `/shared`.
